#Text=Chapter XV
#Text=A forlorn woman went along a lighted avenue .
#Text=The street was filled with people desperately bound on missions .
#Text=An endless crowd darted at the elevated station stairs and the horse cars were thronged with owners of bundles .
#Text=The pace of the forlorn woman was slow .
#Text=She was apparently searching for some one .
#Text=She loitered near the doors of saloons and watched men emerge from them .
#Text=She scanned furtively the faces in the rushing stream of pedestrians .
#Text=Hurrying men , bent on catching some boat or train , jostled her elbows , failing to notice her , their thoughts fixed on distant dinners .
#Text=The forlorn woman had a peculiar face .
#Text=Her smile was no smile .
#Text=But when in repose her features had a shadowy look that was like a sardonic grin , as if some one had sketched with cruel forefinger indelible lines about her mouth .
#Text=Jimmie came strolling up the avenue .
#Text=The woman encountered him with an aggrieved air .
#Text=" Oh , Jimmie , I 've been lookin ' all over fer yehs -- , " she began .
#Text=Jimmie made an impatient gesture and quickened his pace .
#Text=" Ah , do n't bodder me !
#Text=Jimmie turned upon her fiercely as if resolved to make a last stand for comfort and peace .
#Text=" Say , fer Gawd 's sake , Hattie , don ' foller me from one end of deh city teh deh odder .

#Text= But , look-a-here -- "

column1: #Text=Jimmie snarled .
#Text=" Oh , go teh hell . "
#Text=He darted into the front door of a convenient saloon and a moment later came out into the shadows that surrounded the side door .
#Text=On the brilliantly lighted avenue he perceived the forlorn woman dodging about like a scout .
#Text=Jimmie laughed with an air of relief and went away .
#Text=When he arrived home he found his mother clamoring .
#Text=Maggie had returned .
#Text=She stood shivering beneath the torrent of her mother 's wrath .
#Text=" Well , I 'm damned , " said Jimmie in greeting .
#Text=His mother , tottering about the room , pointed a quivering forefinger .
#Text=" Lookut her , Jimmie , lookut her .
#Text=" Dere she stands !

#Text=Young Mag 's come home !

column1: #Text=Through the open door curious eyes stared in at Maggie .
#Text=Children ventured into the room and ogled her , as if they formed the front row at a theatre .
#Text=Women , without , bended toward each other and whispered , nodding their heads with airs of profound philosophy .
#Text=A baby , overcome with curiosity concerning this object at which all were looking , sidled forward and touched her dress , cautiously , as if investigating a red-hot stove .
#Text=Its mother 's voice rang out like a warning trumpet .
#Text=She rushed forward and grabbed her child , casting a terrible look of indignation at the girl .
#Text=Maggie 's mother paced to and fro , addressing the doorful of eyes , expounding like a glib showman at a museum .
#Text=Her voice rang through the building .
#Text=" Dere she stands , " she cried , wheeling suddenly and pointing with dramatic finger .
#Text=" Dere she stands !
#Text=He drew hastily back from her .
#Text=" Well , now , yer a hell of a t'ing , ain ' yeh ? " he said , his lips curling in scorn .
#Text=Radiant virtue sat upon his brow and his repelling hands expressed horror of contamination .
#Text=Maggie turned and went .
#Text=The crowd at the door fell back precipitately .
#Text=A baby falling down in front of the door , wrenched a scream like a wounded animal from its mother .
#Text=Another woman sprang forward and picked it up , with a chivalrous air , as if rescuing a human being from an oncoming express train .
#Text=As the girl passed down through the hall , she went before open doors framing more eyes strangely microscopic , and sending broad beams of inquisitive light into the darkness of her path .
#Text=On the second floor she met the gnarled old woman who possessed the music box .
#Text=" So , " she cried , " ' ere yehs are back again , are yehs ?
